"Wambrook, Somerset, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"abt. 1220–1280":"omkring 1220–1280","1220–1280":"1220–1280","1224–1281":"1224–1281","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","abt. 1220":"omkring 1220","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wambrook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"abt. 1220–1280":"circa 1220–1280","1220–1280":"1220–1280","1224–1281":"1224–1281","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","abt. 1220":"circa 1220","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wambrook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"abt. 1220–1280":"about 1220–1280","1220–1280":"1220–1280","1224–1281":"1224–1281","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","abt. 1220":"about 1220","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wambrook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Oliver","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern), southern Scottish, southern French, and German: from the Old French personal name <i>Oliver</i> (modern French <i>Olivier</i>). This became common largely through the influence of the immensely popular narrative poem <i>Chanson de Roland</i>, in which the warrior Oliver is the wise best friend of the doomed hero Roland. The two men were peers at the court of Charlemagne, and the name is probably of ancient Germanic origin. The name ostensibly means ‘olive tree’ (see   Oliveira  ), but this is almost certainly the result of folk etymology working on an unidentified ancient Germanic personal name, perhaps a cognate of   Alvaro  . Old Norse <i>Óláf</i> (see   Olliff  ) and ancient Germanic <i>Alfhari</i> (composed of the elements <i>alf</i> ‘elf’ and <i>hari</i> ‘army’) have also been suggested as sources, but both personal names are difficult to explain phonetically, especially the latter. The Anglo-Norman name has been established in Ireland (Louth) since at least the 14th century, and was reinforced in Ulster and Limerick by migrants from England in the 17th century. The surname is also borne by Jews, apparently as an adoption of the non-Jewish surname.","Catalan: generally a topographic name from <i>oliver</i> ‘olive tree’, but in some instances possibly related to a homonymous personal name (see 1 above).","History: The surname <i>Oliver</i> of French origin (see 1 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Oliveros","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Pedro, Alfredo, Gilberto, Juan, Arturo, Carlos, Javier, Jesus, Jorge, Luis.","Spanish: from an old variant of the personal name <i>Olivero</i> (see   Oliver  )."]},{"name":"Oliveira","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Luis, Fernando, Mario, Luiz, Francisco, Sergio, Ana, Geraldo, Pedro.  Portuguese Joao, Paulo, Joaquim, Duarte, Agostinho, Guilherme, Marcio, Sebastiao, Anabela, Henrique, Messias, Ademir.","Portuguese and Galician: habitational name from any of numerous places called Oliveira, from Portuguese and Galician <i>oliveira</i> ‘olive grove’ (from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>oliva</i> ‘olive’), or a topographic name from this word. Compare   De Oliveira  .","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Iberian surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."]},{"name":"Oliverson","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic from   Oliver  ."]},{"name":"Oliviero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Amedeo, Aniello, Ciro, Dante, Gennaro, Pasquale, Pietro, Rocco, Salvatore, Silvio, Ugo.  Spanish Mario, Ademar, Guadalupe, Jose, Ricardo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Oliviero</i>, from the Old French personal name <i>Olivier</i> (see   Oliver  )."]},{"name":"Olivier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Jacques, Michel, Andre, Antoine, Julien, Marcel, Armand, Benoit, Edouard, Emile, Henri.","French: from the personal name <i>Olivier</i>, standard French form of   Oliver  ."]},{"name":"Olver","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): variant of   Oliver  ."]},{"name":"Olivero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Luis, Jose, Mercedes, Ana, Andres, Armando, Cesar, Domitila, Dulce, Feliciano, Fernanda, Fernando.  Italian Antonio, Aldo, Carlo, Carmela, Carmelo, Franco, Gabriele, Marco.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Olivero</i> (see   Oliver  ).","Italian: from Old Italian <i>olivero</i>, which, like <i>olivaro</i>, was used to denote an olive tree, and may also have been applied as a nickname for someone who owned or cultivated olive trees."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Oliver was born about 1220, in Wambrook, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Jordan Oliver II Lord of Wambrook, was 21 and his mother, Emma de Belet, was 16. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Emma Belet. He died in 1280, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"abt. 1220–1280":"umbes 1220–1280","1220–1280":"1220–1280","1224–1281":"1224–1281","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","abt. 1220":"umbes 1220","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wambrook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt. 1220–1280":"noin 1220–1280","1220–1280":"1220–1280","1224–1281":"1224–1281","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","abt. 1220":"noin 1220","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wambrook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"abt. 1220–1280":"environ 1220–1280","1220–1280":"1220–1280","1224–1281":"1224–1281","1254–1306":"1254–1306","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1205":"1205","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","abt. 1220":"environ 1220","1264":"1264","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1306":"1306","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Angleterre","Wambrook, Somerset, England":"Wambrook, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Walter Oliver est né environ 1220, à Wambrook, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Lord Jordan Oliver II Lord of Wambrook, avait 21 ans et sa mère, Emma de Belet, avait 16 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Lady Emma Belet. Il est décédé en